  "body": "### Component\n\nAnvil\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [X] Foundry\n- [X] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\nforge 0.2.0 (18791df 2022-12-19T00:10:23.698226Z)\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\n`anvil_setIntervalMining`\n\n### Operating System\n\nNone\n\n### Describe the bug\n\nIn Hardhat, we can programatically disable interval mining by setting the [first parameter of `evm_setIntervalMining` to `0`](https://hardhat.org/hardhat-network/docs/reference#evm_setintervalmining), however, Anvil seems to panic in this case. \r\n\r\nWas just wondering if there is any reason in particular for this?\r\n\r\nThis (potential) bug can be reproduced by adding `api.anvil_set_interval_mining(0)` to the `test_can_change_mining_mode` test:\r\n\r\n```diff\r\nasync fn test_can_change_mining_mode() {\r\n    let (api, handle) = spawn(NodeConfig::test()).await;\r\n    let provider = handle.http_provider();\r\n\r\n    assert!(api.anvil_get_auto_mine().unwrap());\r\n\r\n    let num = provider.get_block_number().await.unwrap();\r\n    assert_eq!(num.as_u64(), 0);\r\n\r\n    api.anvil_set_interval_mining(1).unwrap();\r\n    assert!(!api.anvil_get_auto_mine().unwrap());\r\n    // changing the mining mode will instantly mine a new block\r\n    tokio::time::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_millis(500)).await;\r\n    let num = provider.get_block_number().await.unwrap();\r\n    assert_eq!(num.as_u64(), 0);\r\n\r\n    tokio::time::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_millis(700)).await;\r\n    let num = provider.get_block_number().await.unwrap();\r\n    assert_eq!(num.as_u64(), 1);\r\n\r\n+   // assert that no block is mined when the interval is set to 0\r\n+   api.anvil_set_interval_mining(0).unwrap();\r\n+   tokio::time::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_millis(1000)).await;\r\n+   let num = provider.get_block_number().await.unwrap();\r\n+   assert_eq!(num.as_u64(), 1);\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n",
